WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.198 --> 00:00:02.781
(upbeat music)

2
00:00:07.950 --> 00:00:11.190 line:15% 
<v ->Back to issues related to cardiovascular.</v>

3
00:00:11.190 --> 00:00:13.470 line:15% 
And for that, Dr. Firnhaber is returning,

4
00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:16.110 line:15% 
and we're going to focus our time

5
00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:20.550 line:15% 
on high blood pressure and hypertension.

6
00:00:20.550 --> 00:00:22.680
Learning objectives: We're gonna talk about hypertension.

7
00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:24.300
All right, let's move forward.

8
00:00:24.300 --> 00:00:25.740
So here's some important things to know.

9
00:00:25.740 --> 00:00:27.300
I mean, one, you always have to start with,

10
00:00:27.300 --> 00:00:29.010
here's why this is an important topic.

11
00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:30.120
So independent risk factor

12
00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:32.070
for ischemic cardiovascular events.

13
00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:34.020
As a matter of fact, it is one of the most,

14
00:00:34.020 --> 00:00:37.680
if not the most significant worldwide risk factor

15
00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.110
for cardiovascular disease.

16
00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:41.520
Here's the part that's really cool.

17
00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.260
So if you're trying to mentally wrap your head

18
00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:49.170
around how risky is this patient's blood pressure,

19
00:00:49.170 --> 00:00:50.970
who is sitting in front of me?

20
00:00:50.970 --> 00:00:51.803
If you were to start

21
00:00:51.803 --> 00:00:55.590
with a theoretically normal blood pressure of 115/75,

22
00:00:55.590 --> 00:00:58.500
for every 20 millimeter systolic increase,

23
00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.120
10 millimeter diastolic increase,

24
00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:02.310
you double cardiovascular risk.

25
00:01:02.310 --> 00:01:04.380
Meaning, if someone's sitting in front of you

26
00:01:04.380 --> 00:01:07.050
at 155 systolic, they've had two doublings.

27
00:01:07.050 --> 00:01:09.990
So now they've quadrupled their cardiovascular risk,

28
00:01:09.990 --> 00:01:11.880
they're coming in at 175,

29
00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:13.980
eightfold increase in risk.

30
00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:16.170
So it's something that you'd kind of intuitively think

31
00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:17.940
it's more linear, when in reality

32
00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:20.880
it's actually more of a log linear relationship.

33
00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:23.190
We do recognize that treatment of hypertension

34
00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:25.980
decreases cardiovascular events,

35
00:01:25.980 --> 00:01:29.133
also improves left ventricular hypertrophy.

36
00:01:30.990 --> 00:01:34.080
Have you struggled to follow hypertension guidelines?

37
00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.300
There are new ones coming out soon, by the way,

38
00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:38.130
and we're hoping if, right,

39
00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:42.270
oh boy, that there's gonna be some kind of harmonization.

40
00:01:42.270 --> 00:01:45.930
There was a recent paper that was released by,

41
00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:48.240
it came out from actually a European Society of Cardiology,

42
00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:50.130
European Society of Hypertension,

43
00:01:50.130 --> 00:01:53.490
that attempted to reconcile the ACC/AHA guidelines,

44
00:01:53.490 --> 00:01:55.290
which I'll talk about in just a minute,

45
00:01:55.290 --> 00:01:58.920
very, very aggressive guidelines compared to JNC 8,

46
00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:00.780
and the European guidelines,

47
00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:03.210
which are somewhat in between JNC 8,

48
00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:05.400
which is like, "Meh, your blood pressure's a bit elevated,

49
00:02:05.400 --> 00:02:07.290
it's fine, don't worry."

50
00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:09.300
And then we turned around a couple years later

51
00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:11.820
and said, no, your blood pressure's this much elevated,

52
00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.160
oh my god, you're gonna die today.

53
00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:18.150
So we've got these two almost dichotomous guidelines.

54
00:02:18.150 --> 00:02:20.070
The European guidelines are somewhat in the middle

55
00:02:20.070 --> 00:02:22.380
and there's an attempt to at least reconcile

56
00:02:22.380 --> 00:02:25.170
on a more of a worldly approach to say,

57
00:02:25.170 --> 00:02:27.393
how really should we address blood pressure?

58
00:02:28.350 --> 00:02:30.450
So JNC 8 is now 10 years old,

59
00:02:30.450 --> 00:02:33.750
which I still, our EHR by the way still says

60
00:02:33.750 --> 00:02:35.100
according to JNC 8,

61
00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:38.190
and I type back to the people that send this in there,

62
00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:41.100
it's a 10-year-old guideline, should we not update this?

63
00:02:41.100 --> 00:02:43.650
Well, this is still what people like to do.

64
00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:47.940
Okay, so JNC 8 has some good parts and some bad parts.

65
00:02:47.940 --> 00:02:50.550
Number one, it was a very evidence-based guideline,

66
00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:52.980
which is why it took so long to come out,

67
00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:57.840
JNC Late, JNC Wait, there was all sorts of clever words

68
00:02:57.840 --> 00:02:58.710
that we used for it.

69
00:02:58.710 --> 00:03:01.470
But it was an attempt to be much more evidence-based

70
00:03:01.470 --> 00:03:04.053
than JNC 7, which is an atrocious guideline.

71
00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:06.540
Parts of JNC 8 were good.

72
00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:09.600
So JNC 8 said a general population under age 60,

73
00:03:09.600 --> 00:03:13.170
including those with CKD, including those with diabetes,

74
00:03:13.170 --> 00:03:16.950
you make the diagnosis with either a systolic blood pressure

75
00:03:16.950 --> 00:03:19.710
of 140 or a diastolic of 90.

76
00:03:19.710 --> 00:03:22.650
And in order to actually have achieved your goal,

77
00:03:22.650 --> 00:03:26.400
you have to have both less than 140 less than 90.

78
00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:28.200
Here's the part about JNC 8

79
00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:29.400
that really upset people.

80
00:03:29.400 --> 00:03:33.420
It is the cutoff at age 60 to say at age 60,

81
00:03:33.420 --> 00:03:36.480
you can relax on your systolic threshold for treatment

82
00:03:36.480 --> 00:03:38.400
and your target for treatment.

83
00:03:38.400 --> 00:03:39.960
The concept is sound,

84
00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:42.840
and most every other guideline in the whole freaking world

85
00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:45.630
does this, but says at its age 80,

86
00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:47.760
recognizing that at some point

87
00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:49.830
as patients become more frail,

88
00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:51.780
and it's always hard to define frailty

89
00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:53.640
simply by an age number,

90
00:03:53.640 --> 00:03:55.950
but as patients become more frail,

91
00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:57.660
aggressive blood pressure lowering

92
00:03:57.660 --> 00:03:59.460
may become more problematic.

93
00:03:59.460 --> 00:04:00.990
And you run the risk of,

94
00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:03.600
if you're aggressively lowering systolic pressure,

95
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:05.490
diastolic can follow.

96
00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:06.960
Patients who as they age,

97
00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:09.330
they tend to have more coronary atherosclerosis,

98
00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:11.610
they tend to have widened pulse pressures,

99
00:04:11.610 --> 00:04:13.800
higher systolic, lower diastolic.

100
00:04:13.800 --> 00:04:16.680
And if you push diastolic lower and lower,

101
00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:19.230
remember when do the coronary arteries perfuse?

102
00:04:19.230 --> 00:04:20.730
During diastole.

103
00:04:20.730 --> 00:04:22.530
Diastolic pressures less than 60

104
00:04:22.530 --> 00:04:25.110
run the risk of coronary malperfusion.

105
00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:26.160
So there are risks

106
00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:29.910
to aggressively lowering blood pressure in older patients.

107
00:04:29.910 --> 00:04:32.160
The question is, should you make the cutoff at age 60,

108
00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:35.370
which seems inappropriately low for a lot of people,

109
00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:37.200
or should it be a higher age?

110
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:38.913
But that's what JNC 8 said.

111
00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:42.750
2017 guidelines, which came out just a couple years later,

112
00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:44.790
right, as we were still kind of getting adjusted

113
00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:48.000
to JNC 8 being a little bit relaxed, said,

114
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.420
our threshold for most everybody

115
00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:54.030
who is at low risk is still gonna be 140/90.

116
00:04:54.030 --> 00:04:57.660
However, our target's always less than 130/80.

117
00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:01.020
And the primary driver for this set of guidelines

118
00:05:01.020 --> 00:05:02.310
was the "SPRINT" trial,

119
00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:05.520
which basically looked at what was considered

120
00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:06.510
kind of standard of care

121
00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:08.910
versus more aggressive blood pressure lowering,

122
00:05:08.910 --> 00:05:11.497
found that in patients without diabetes,

123
00:05:11.497 --> 00:05:13.350
"SPRINT" was a trial

124
00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:15.810
that did not include patients with diabetes,

125
00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:18.990
specifically, that aggressive blood pressure lowering

126
00:05:18.990 --> 00:05:20.760
did improve outcome some.

127
00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.340
There was some increase in renal outcomes,

128
00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:25.230
people had worsening creatinine,

129
00:05:25.230 --> 00:05:27.120
they tended to fall a little bit more.

130
00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:29.910
But in the end, there was better data

131
00:05:29.910 --> 00:05:32.370
to say more aggressive blood pressure lowering

132
00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:33.780
is a good thing.

133
00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:34.890
The reason incidentally "SPRINT"

134
00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:36.270
didn't include patient with diabetes

135
00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:38.910
is that the "ACCORD BP,"

136
00:05:38.910 --> 00:05:41.460
the blood pressure arm of the "ACCORD" trial

137
00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:43.800
basically did the same study,

138
00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:45.390
except in patients with diabetes,

139
00:05:45.390 --> 00:05:47.340
saw a no incremental benefit

140
00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.440
to more aggressive blood pressure lowering.

141
00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.500
So one of the criticisms of the 2017 guidelines

142
00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:54.037
is that it was very "SPRINT" driven,

143
00:05:54.037 --> 00:05:57.000
"SPRINT" had its pluses and minuses as well.

144
00:05:57.000 --> 00:05:59.370
But you'll see that in secondary prevention,

145
00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:01.050
people who are higher risk,

146
00:06:01.050 --> 00:06:04.560
this guideline is recommending 130/80 as our threshold,

147
00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:07.743
and 130/80 almost always as our target.

148
00:06:08.790 --> 00:06:11.557
You're probably aware AAFP said,

149
00:06:11.557 --> 00:06:14.970
"We like JNC 8 better, we don't like the new guidelines."

150
00:06:14.970 --> 00:06:18.570
And this was not an unpopular stance by the way.

151
00:06:18.570 --> 00:06:21.660
So if you're kind of curious on the exam,

152
00:06:21.660 --> 00:06:23.640
'cause the question comes down to the exam, right,

153
00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:26.910
which one are we going to be asked about?

154
00:06:26.910 --> 00:06:27.990
I would be familiar with both.

155
00:06:27.990 --> 00:06:29.340
I'd be familiar with the idea

156
00:06:29.340 --> 00:06:32.970
that we have competing guidelines for hypertension.

157
00:06:32.970 --> 00:06:36.390
The real answer is probably someplace in between those.

158
00:06:36.390 --> 00:06:39.810
JNC 8 says we have to be a bit cautious in patients

159
00:06:39.810 --> 00:06:43.500
as they age to not aggressively lower blood pressure.

160
00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.450
The next set of guidelines that came out three years later

161
00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:48.600
said there is data showing that in many patients,

162
00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:50.040
more aggressive blood pressure lowering

163
00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:51.810
does improve outcomes,

164
00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:54.750
but it's always a risk versus benefit evaluation.

165
00:06:54.750 --> 00:06:57.210
So in a frail risky patient,

166
00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:59.910
you may not wanna lower blood pressure quite as aggressively

167
00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:02.910
in someone who can tolerate 130/80 or lower

168
00:07:02.910 --> 00:07:04.860
without undue treatment side effects,

169
00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:06.693
fantastic, move in that direction.

170
00:07:09.090 --> 00:07:11.430
One thing that did change in the transition

171
00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:14.580
from JNC 8 to the newest ACC/AHA guidelines

172
00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:15.810
was an increased emphasis

173
00:07:15.810 --> 00:07:18.420
on out-of-office blood pressure measurements.

174
00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:21.360
Invariably this is going to come up on the exam.

175
00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:23.670
Recognizing that the blood pressure

176
00:07:23.670 --> 00:07:25.650
that we typically get in clinic,

177
00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:27.930
patient had a little incident in the parking lot,

178
00:07:27.930 --> 00:07:29.010
they wanted this parking spot,

179
00:07:29.010 --> 00:07:29.910
someone else parked in it,

180
00:07:29.910 --> 00:07:31.560
then they had to walk all the way in,

181
00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:33.270
pay a co-payment and get weighed,

182
00:07:33.270 --> 00:07:34.830
and then they sit down in the exam room

183
00:07:34.830 --> 00:07:36.870
and get their blood pressure checked,

184
00:07:36.870 --> 00:07:38.700
is that really an accurate blood pressure?

185
00:07:38.700 --> 00:07:40.020
Does that truly describe

186
00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:43.410
what this patient's overall blood pressure is likely to be?

187
00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:44.460
Probably not.

188
00:07:44.460 --> 00:07:46.500
So out-of-office blood pressure measurements

189
00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:48.870
are becoming more and more the norm,

190
00:07:48.870 --> 00:07:53.700
and really the drive to get more data to say,

191
00:07:53.700 --> 00:07:56.430
is this one blood pressure in the office really predictive?

192
00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:58.350
Or if we have more and more data,

193
00:07:58.350 --> 00:08:00.570
whether it's ambulatory blood pressure monitoring,

194
00:08:00.570 --> 00:08:02.670
home blood pressure monitoring,

195
00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.770
I disagree that Walmart blood pressure monitoring

196
00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:07.020
is a good thing, I get hives and hypertension

197
00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:08.190
when I go to Walmart,

198
00:08:08.190 --> 00:08:10.800
so probably a bad place to check your blood pressure.

199
00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:13.800
But out-of-office blood pressure monitoring is a good thing.

200
00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.170
And those out-of-office numbers

201
00:08:16.170 --> 00:08:19.110
typically have better predictive value

202
00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:21.930
than your in-office numbers that you may get,

203
00:08:21.930 --> 00:08:23.583
one value every three months.

204
00:08:25.230 --> 00:08:27.750
Really what we're trying to ferret out

205
00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:30.840
is white coat versus masked hypertension.

206
00:08:30.840 --> 00:08:33.720
And white coat hypertension as you're probably aware,

207
00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:36.270
is patient comes to clinic, their blood pressure's elevated

208
00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:37.740
and they say, "No, no, I keep checking.

209
00:08:37.740 --> 00:08:40.200
Here's all my home numbers, they look great."

210
00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:41.340
They bring their blood pressure cuff,

211
00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.230
and their cuff is reading accurately.

212
00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:46.380
So the good thing is that white coat hypertension is,

213
00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:48.000
from a cardiovascular risk standpoint,

214
00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:49.293
is not all that risky.

215
00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:52.650
Masked hypertension is just the opposite.

216
00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:54.300
That's when they look good in clinic

217
00:08:54.300 --> 00:08:55.740
and then they go out of clinic

218
00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:57.190
and their numbers are higher.

219
00:08:58.110 --> 00:09:01.080
This is a much more risky situation in the...

220
00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.390
If you're asking what's the clinical situation,

221
00:09:03.390 --> 00:09:05.310
short acting antihypertensive drugs

222
00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:07.230
are typically what causes this.

223
00:09:07.230 --> 00:09:11.130
So a short acting beta blocker, atenolol for example,

224
00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:14.043
short-acting dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers,

225
00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:18.300
any short acting beta blocker for example

226
00:09:18.300 --> 00:09:20.640
taken in the morning, patient comes in that morning,

227
00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:23.610
their blood pressure looks better, they go home,

228
00:09:23.610 --> 00:09:25.530
the blood pressure medication

229
00:09:25.530 --> 00:09:28.470
that lasts for less than 24 hours starts to taper off,

230
00:09:28.470 --> 00:09:29.930
and their blood pressure ratchets up

231
00:09:29.930 --> 00:09:32.040
in the evening and overnight hours,

232
00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:33.420
which is masked hypertension.

233
00:09:33.420 --> 00:09:36.870
And that actually has significant cardiovascular risk.

234
00:09:36.870 --> 00:09:38.790
Prevalence data is really hard to come by

235
00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:40.380
because we don't have much

236
00:09:40.380 --> 00:09:42.540
ambulatory blood pressure monitoring information

237
00:09:42.540 --> 00:09:43.950
for most of our patients.

238
00:09:43.950 --> 00:09:46.750
But we do recognize that masked hypertension is a worry.

239
00:09:47.730 --> 00:09:48.993
What about kids?

240
00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:52.890
Big thing to recall is that there are tables

241
00:09:52.890 --> 00:09:56.940
for what is the blood pressure percentile range

242
00:09:56.940 --> 00:09:58.770
based on age, gender, and height.

243
00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:01.440
And if you think that you can look

244
00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:02.550
at a child's blood pressure

245
00:10:02.550 --> 00:10:05.670
and intuitively know if it's okay or not okay,

246
00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:07.080
you're way smarter than I am

247
00:10:07.080 --> 00:10:09.690
'cause every time I think, "That doesn't look too bad."

248
00:10:09.690 --> 00:10:10.687
Then you look at the chart, it's like

249
00:10:10.687 --> 00:10:12.960
"Oh my goodness, it is high."

250
00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:17.100
So if your EHR doesn't calculate that, use the tables.

251
00:10:17.100 --> 00:10:18.810
I would encourage you not to rely on your memory,

252
00:10:18.810 --> 00:10:20.670
but recognize age, gender, height,

253
00:10:20.670 --> 00:10:22.530
are the variables that go along

254
00:10:22.530 --> 00:10:25.560
with blood pressure for kids.

255
00:10:25.560 --> 00:10:26.430
Most of the time when we see

256
00:10:26.430 --> 00:10:27.540
elevated blood pressure in kids,

257
00:10:27.540 --> 00:10:30.600
it's due to obesity, sleep apnea is actually starting

258
00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:32.640
to increase kind of nudge its way up

259
00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:36.840
in terms of the other triggers for elevated blood pressure.

260
00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:38.730
Think also about congenital problems,

261
00:10:38.730 --> 00:10:41.880
renal vascular disease, renal parenchymal disease,

262
00:10:41.880 --> 00:10:44.400
rheumatologic disorders, and so on.

263
00:10:44.400 --> 00:10:47.640
Evaluation, the guidelines that are out there

264
00:10:47.640 --> 00:10:49.743
are kind of variable.

265
00:10:50.850 --> 00:10:53.550
Chemistry, lipids, blood sugar, are all reasonable things.

266
00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:55.260
Whether or not to get an echo,

267
00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:56.970
whether or not to get a renal ultrasound,

268
00:10:56.970 --> 00:11:00.090
is variable depending on which guideline you look at.

269
00:11:00.090 --> 00:11:02.160
But consider some advanced imaging

270
00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:04.500
to say is there echocardiographic evidence

271
00:11:04.500 --> 00:11:06.660
of say LVH, coarctation,

272
00:11:06.660 --> 00:11:08.850
anything that would make you worried,

273
00:11:08.850 --> 00:11:11.340
and renal disease as well.

274
00:11:11.340 --> 00:11:14.520
Most often weight loss and exercise are high on the list.

275
00:11:14.520 --> 00:11:16.740
So let's move to a question.

276
00:11:16.740 --> 00:11:19.170
All right, we've got a 48-year-old female

277
00:11:19.170 --> 00:11:21.180
who presents to clinic as a new patient.

278
00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.730
BP 172/110 in both arms.

279
00:11:23.730 --> 00:11:26.790
Her BMI is 24.

280
00:11:26.790 --> 00:11:28.440
Unremarkable exam, no meds,

281
00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:30.450
no OTC supplements.

282
00:11:30.450 --> 00:11:32.580
Chemistry, the only thing that's notable

283
00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:35.220
is a potassium of 3.3 on no medications,

284
00:11:35.220 --> 00:11:36.930
creatinine is fine.

285
00:11:36.930 --> 00:11:40.350
If her hypertension should prove refractory to treatment,

286
00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:41.970
which one of the following is most likely

287
00:11:41.970 --> 00:11:45.360
to reveal the cause of her elevated blood pressure.

288
00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:47.310
So what are you thinking this might be?

289
00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:51.540
And would you wanna check 24-hour urine catecholamines,

290
00:11:51.540 --> 00:11:54.480
an aldosterone to renin ratio,

291
00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:56.280
do an MRA of the renal arteries,

292
00:11:56.280 --> 00:11:57.963
or a sleep study?

293
00:12:03.120 --> 00:12:07.080
Great, so most are going with an aldosterone to renin ratio.

294
00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:08.790
'Cause really the description here

295
00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:12.867
is leading you down the path of primary hyperaldosteronism.

296
00:12:13.830 --> 00:12:17.550
And this is probably more common than we realize

297
00:12:17.550 --> 00:12:19.470
because we use drugs that block

298
00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:21.960
the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system all the time

299
00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:24.030
and likely treat a bunch of this

300
00:12:24.030 --> 00:12:25.200
without even knowing it,

301
00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.300
without actually diagnosing it.

302
00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:30.510
More common in those who have resistant hypertension.

303
00:12:30.510 --> 00:12:33.270
The hypokalemia part, if you're wanting to hang on that

304
00:12:33.270 --> 00:12:35.130
to say you always have to see hypokalemia

305
00:12:35.130 --> 00:12:37.620
to make the diagnosis, not so.

306
00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:42.210
It's helpful, but it's not necessary to make the diagnosis.

307
00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:44.100
It's the aldosterone to renin ratio.

308
00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:46.380
Aldosterone, A comes before R,

309
00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.500
so that's how I remember which one goes on top.

310
00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:50.580
Don't remember numbers

311
00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:53.460
because different labs report aldosterone region

312
00:12:53.460 --> 00:12:54.810
in different units

313
00:12:54.810 --> 00:12:56.790
and obviously the units make a difference

314
00:12:56.790 --> 00:12:58.950
in how the numbers pan out.

315
00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:01.020
So if you remember this part

316
00:13:01.020 --> 00:13:03.660
that you have to order serum aldosterone and renin,

317
00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:04.620
first thing in the morning,

318
00:13:04.620 --> 00:13:06.480
and ideally off of any drug

319
00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:08.880
that impacts the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system

320
00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:11.490
for at least two weeks can be problematic.

321
00:13:11.490 --> 00:13:14.040
So this is why we don't do it all the time.

322
00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:16.770
Sleep apnea for adults has now moved to the very top.

323
00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:18.570
It used to be other things,

324
00:13:18.570 --> 00:13:20.040
we're seeing more and more sleep apnea,

325
00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:21.540
whether it's more prevalent

326
00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:23.040
or we're just recognizing it more,

327
00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:26.340
it's now the leading cause of secondary hypertension,

328
00:13:26.340 --> 00:13:28.503
and think of that often.

329
00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:33.180
If you're thinking about maybe this is renal artery stenosis

330
00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:35.730
in those under age 30, fibromuscular disease,

331
00:13:35.730 --> 00:13:37.920
which tends to be more congenital

332
00:13:37.920 --> 00:13:39.510
is typically the cause.

333
00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:41.040
But over age 30, actually,

334
00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:42.930
is where atherosclerotic disease

335
00:13:42.930 --> 00:13:45.630
starts to take over the fibromuscular disease.

336
00:13:45.630 --> 00:13:49.020
And we recognize the complications,

337
00:13:49.020 --> 00:13:52.650
difficult to control hypertension, flash pulmonary edema.

338
00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:55.980
Remember ACE inhibitors/ARBs may worsen the situation

339
00:13:55.980 --> 00:13:57.930
'cause in essence the the one kidney

340
00:13:57.930 --> 00:13:59.850
that is actually being perfused,

341
00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:01.710
if it's unilateral renal artery stenosis

342
00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:04.620
is pumping out a ton of renin and aldosterone

343
00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:07.860
trying to maintain blood pressure, maintain perfusion.

344
00:14:07.860 --> 00:14:10.230
And so that will worsen renal function

345
00:14:10.230 --> 00:14:12.453
if you add an ACEI/ARB on top of that.

346
00:14:13.350 --> 00:14:15.390
The gold standard diagnosis is an MRA,

347
00:14:15.390 --> 00:14:19.020
although for screening, just a simple renal ultrasound,

348
00:14:19.020 --> 00:14:22.020
and if you direct attention to the renal arteries,

349
00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:23.640
if you've got normal renal artery flow

350
00:14:23.640 --> 00:14:25.110
by a doppler ultrasound,

351
00:14:25.110 --> 00:14:27.450
you can cross the diagnosis off the list.

352
00:14:27.450 --> 00:14:29.700
And the frustrating thing here

353
00:14:29.700 --> 00:14:32.130
is one would think that opening up,

354
00:14:32.130 --> 00:14:34.680
and we open up arteries all over the place,

355
00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:36.480
in the heart, in the legs,

356
00:14:36.480 --> 00:14:37.620
opening up the renal arteries

357
00:14:37.620 --> 00:14:39.570
doesn't actually improve outcomes.

358
00:14:39.570 --> 00:14:41.760
There is one trial, the "ROOSTER" trial,

359
00:14:41.760 --> 00:14:43.350
which I love the acronym,

360
00:14:43.350 --> 00:14:45.720
that is looking more closely at other outcomes

361
00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:48.870
with renal artery stenosis, data's not there yet.

362
00:14:48.870 --> 00:14:51.930
But for now, revascularization of renal arteries

363
00:14:51.930 --> 00:14:54.690
except in very few situations,

364
00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:56.910
and I leave those to our vascular surgeons

365
00:14:56.910 --> 00:14:57.930
in very few situations

366
00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:00.430
where there's actually benefit to revascularizing.

367
00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:05.070
Most other causes of secondary hypertension,

368
00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:06.600
either the stuff we learned in medical school

369
00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:08.880
we'll never see like pheochromocytomas,

370
00:15:08.880 --> 00:15:11.160
and probably in a room this size,

371
00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:13.650
two people have seen a few, maybe three,

372
00:15:13.650 --> 00:15:15.060
maybe four, something like that,

373
00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:16.200
not many hands, right?

374
00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:19.200
It's not like 75% of people raise their hand,

375
00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:21.060
it's pretty uncommon.

376
00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:23.670
Thyroid disease, kidney disease high on the list,

377
00:15:23.670 --> 00:15:25.470
and then all the drugs that people take

378
00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:27.813
and don't tell you about are high on the list.

379
00:15:28.710 --> 00:15:30.240
All right, let's move to another question.

380
00:15:30.240 --> 00:15:32.880
We've got a 58-year-old woman

381
00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:35.190
who has a home BP of 155/95

382
00:15:35.190 --> 00:15:37.080
confirmed by multiple similar readings

383
00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:40.530
and office BP that is similar as well.

384
00:15:40.530 --> 00:15:41.490
She does all the right things.

385
00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:43.380
She exercises, follows a low salt diet,

386
00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:45.300
rarely drinks alcohol.

387
00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:47.220
Which one of the following medications

388
00:15:47.220 --> 00:15:48.240
would be most appropriate

389
00:15:48.240 --> 00:15:50.913
as initial therapy for this patient?

390
00:15:52.470 --> 00:15:53.940
So we've got chlorthalidone,

391
00:15:53.940 --> 00:15:58.383
clonidine, doxazosin, and metoprolol.

392
00:16:03.810 --> 00:16:05.130
Wow, 96%.

393
00:16:05.130 --> 00:16:06.660
And would you have chosen chlorthalidone

394
00:16:06.660 --> 00:16:08.610
if I put HCTZ on there?

395
00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:10.590
Probably not, not as much.

396
00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:12.180
And the other drugs are ones

397
00:16:12.180 --> 00:16:15.300
that we rarely reach for other than beta blockers,

398
00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:17.970
which haven't appeared in a JNC guideline

399
00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:20.610
since either JNC 5 or 6.

400
00:16:20.610 --> 00:16:23.790
It's been a long time since beta blockers were on the list.

401
00:16:23.790 --> 00:16:25.587
So here's what JNC 8

402
00:16:25.587 --> 00:16:29.403
and also the 2017 guidelines say about drugs.

403
00:16:30.540 --> 00:16:33.000
Top of the list, in the general non-Black population,

404
00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:35.160
we've got four drug classes that we can pick,

405
00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:37.380
any of them are considered acceptable.

406
00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:40.200
And granted there are clinical situations

407
00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:43.590
which may drive us to pick one or the other,

408
00:16:43.590 --> 00:16:46.380
but we recognize that they're all relatively equal

409
00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:48.540
in terms of CV outcomes data.

410
00:16:48.540 --> 00:16:51.450
So ACE inhibitor/ARB, thiazide diuretic,

411
00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:54.450
which should be HCTZ, thiazide-like diuretic,

412
00:16:54.450 --> 00:16:56.670
which should be chlorthalidone or indapamide

413
00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:58.830
or calcium channel blocker.

414
00:16:58.830 --> 00:17:00.540
The implication here is always that it is

415
00:17:00.540 --> 00:17:03.540
a long-acting dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker,

416
00:17:03.540 --> 00:17:06.330
meaning not verapamil, not diltiazem,

417
00:17:06.330 --> 00:17:09.960
not immediate release nifedipine,

418
00:17:09.960 --> 00:17:11.460
if you can still find that.

419
00:17:11.460 --> 00:17:14.493
So long-acting dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker.

420
00:17:15.960 --> 00:17:18.300
The follow-up statement is in the general Black population,

421
00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:20.760
including those with diabetes,

422
00:17:20.760 --> 00:17:22.950
initial treatment should include a thiazide diuretic

423
00:17:22.950 --> 00:17:25.020
or a calcium channel blocker.

424
00:17:25.020 --> 00:17:27.270
Recognizing that in Black patients,

425
00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:29.160
and if you're curious, these studies,

426
00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:31.290
the researchers didn't have people parade

427
00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:33.930
in front of them and decide ethnicity,

428
00:17:33.930 --> 00:17:35.940
it's how patients self-identify.

429
00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:36.960
So if you wanted to add

430
00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:40.200
in the general self-identified Black population,

431
00:17:40.200 --> 00:17:42.180
that might be appropriate as well.

432
00:17:42.180 --> 00:17:44.340
But we do recognize that in that population,

433
00:17:44.340 --> 00:17:46.350
ACE inhibitors, ARBs,

434
00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:48.690
and incidentally beta blockers,

435
00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:52.380
as monotherapy, typically work less well

436
00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:54.240
from a blood pressure reduction

437
00:17:54.240 --> 00:17:57.630
and a cardiovascular outcome standpoint.

438
00:17:57.630 --> 00:18:00.390
Meaning don't use those drugs at all,

439
00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:03.450
just saying if you're picking drugs as initial therapy

440
00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:06.060
and you want a drug that's gonna lower blood pressure best

441
00:18:06.060 --> 00:18:07.770
and give you best outcomes,

442
00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:10.620
calcium channel blockers thiazides typically work better.

443
00:18:12.090 --> 00:18:14.143
So in those over 18 with chronic kidney disease,

444
00:18:14.143 --> 00:18:16.890
an ACEI or ARB should be on the list somewhere.

445
00:18:16.890 --> 00:18:18.150
If it's not initial therapy,

446
00:18:18.150 --> 00:18:19.950
at least needs to be add-on therapy.

447
00:18:21.030 --> 00:18:22.170
All sorts of guidance now

448
00:18:22.170 --> 00:18:26.220
that we just don't mix ARBs and ACE inhibitors,

449
00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:28.740
we recognize that neither one of them fully suppresses

450
00:18:28.740 --> 00:18:30.750
the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.

451
00:18:30.750 --> 00:18:32.467
So there was some thought for a while,

452
00:18:32.467 --> 00:18:34.860
"What if we add the two together?"

453
00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:36.270
Renal outcomes worsened,

454
00:18:36.270 --> 00:18:37.920
cardiovascular outcomes didn't improve,

455
00:18:37.920 --> 00:18:39.060
everything just went bad,

456
00:18:39.060 --> 00:18:41.163
so we don't mix those two together.

457
00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:44.460
What I like most about JNC 8

458
00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:46.560
is actually the final recommendation.

459
00:18:46.560 --> 00:18:48.750
It was the ninth of the recommendations,

460
00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:51.480
and it basically says our objective

461
00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:53.670
is to identify hypertension

462
00:18:53.670 --> 00:18:56.040
and pick drugs that lower blood pressure

463
00:18:56.040 --> 00:18:59.040
and keep doing that until we get blood pressure to goal.

464
00:18:59.040 --> 00:19:01.350
Meaning we're looking at the endpoint,

465
00:19:01.350 --> 00:19:03.510
we're a bit less concerned about the path

466
00:19:03.510 --> 00:19:06.390
that we have to take to get to that endpoint.

467
00:19:06.390 --> 00:19:08.190
Our goal is to simply identify blood pressure

468
00:19:08.190 --> 00:19:09.690
and get blood pressure to goal.

469
00:19:09.690 --> 00:19:11.340
If it takes three drugs, if it takes two drugs,

470
00:19:11.340 --> 00:19:13.440
you pick this first, you pick this next,

471
00:19:13.440 --> 00:19:15.090
you take this drug and ramp it all up

472
00:19:15.090 --> 00:19:16.590
before you add something else,

473
00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:18.840
to use a couple different drugs in low dose,

474
00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:20.520
hmm, not quite as relevant.

475
00:19:20.520 --> 00:19:22.140
The goal is to get to the endpoint,

476
00:19:22.140 --> 00:19:23.740
which is a lower blood pressure.

477
00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:25.773
So how do we decide?

478
00:19:26.730 --> 00:19:28.200
So thiazide diuretics,

479
00:19:28.200 --> 00:19:29.970
typically more effective than ACE inhibitors

480
00:19:29.970 --> 00:19:31.320
for improving heart failure

481
00:19:31.320 --> 00:19:34.380
and cardiovascular outcomes in African American patients,

482
00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:37.710
that came from one of the most landmark hypertension trials,

483
00:19:37.710 --> 00:19:39.570
the "ALLHAT" trial.

484
00:19:39.570 --> 00:19:42.030
Incidentally, "ALLHAT" also gave us guidance

485
00:19:42.030 --> 00:19:44.970
that we don't use alpha blocker monotherapy.

486
00:19:44.970 --> 00:19:47.370
That arm of "ALLHAT" was actually stopped early

487
00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:49.590
because of adverse outcomes.

488
00:19:49.590 --> 00:19:52.080
But alpha blocker is still very reasonable choices

489
00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:54.633
as drug four or drug five for example.

490
00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:57.330
Reducing strokes, calcium channel blocker

491
00:19:57.330 --> 00:19:59.670
is also more effective than ACE inhibitors,

492
00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:03.000
and certainly for ARBs as well.

493
00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:05.760
We do recognize that in CKD heart failure

494
00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:07.080
ethnicity disappears,

495
00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:10.653
we use ACE inhibitors/ARBs preferentially there.

496
00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:14.820
What about thiazides or thiazide-like diuretics?

497
00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:16.110
Pluses and minuses.

498
00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.870
So very likely, I don't know that,

499
00:20:18.870 --> 00:20:21.630
I've taken the exam like four times,

500
00:20:21.630 --> 00:20:22.980
there's always been a question

501
00:20:22.980 --> 00:20:24.337
that reads something like,

502
00:20:24.337 --> 00:20:27.570
"You have a patient with hypertension and osteoporosis.

503
00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:31.710
What drug will decrease urinary calcium excretion?"

504
00:20:31.710 --> 00:20:35.040
Thiazide diuretics decrease urinary calcium excretion.

505
00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:37.800
That also means that for someone who has hypercalciuria,

506
00:20:37.800 --> 00:20:39.810
this is a useful drug as well.

507
00:20:39.810 --> 00:20:43.290
They do increase the excretion

508
00:20:43.290 --> 00:20:45.870
or decrease the excretion of uric acid.

509
00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:48.330
If someone has asymptomatic hyperuricemia,

510
00:20:48.330 --> 00:20:50.970
it is still asymptomatic hyperuricemia,

511
00:20:50.970 --> 00:20:52.170
thiazide is fine.

512
00:20:52.170 --> 00:20:53.700
Someone has history of gout,

513
00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:55.560
it is no longer asymptomatic hyperuricemia.

514
00:20:55.560 --> 00:20:58.350
Thiazide diuretics can worsen that

515
00:20:58.350 --> 00:21:01.530
just 'cause they can increase uric acid levels.

516
00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:04.083
If you do have patients that still take lithium,

517
00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:07.890
thiazides decrease lithium excretion,

518
00:21:07.890 --> 00:21:10.773
it's become a less and less commonly seen drug.

519
00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:15.630
Potassium excretion certainly increases with a thiazide.

520
00:21:15.630 --> 00:21:16.920
Here's an interesting point though,

521
00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:20.460
is that the patients who have the most potassium loss

522
00:21:20.460 --> 00:21:22.320
with a thiazide are those

523
00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:25.353
that have the highest dietary sodium intake.

524
00:21:26.280 --> 00:21:29.070
Meaning, one approach to managing

525
00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:32.220
the hypokalemia seen with a thiazide diuretic

526
00:21:32.220 --> 00:21:34.110
is having your patient decrease

527
00:21:34.110 --> 00:21:36.150
their dietary sodium intake.

528
00:21:36.150 --> 00:21:38.160
You can replace the potassium with a supplement

529
00:21:38.160 --> 00:21:39.660
or take in less sodium,

530
00:21:39.660 --> 00:21:43.590
and therefore excrete less potassium, two options.

531
00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:45.750
Finally, it's great that with BMP

532
00:21:45.750 --> 00:21:48.840
is now a CHEM-8 and has calcium on there.

533
00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:51.480
I wish to the world that it was a CHEM-9

534
00:21:51.480 --> 00:21:53.100
and we always got a magnesium,

535
00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:54.690
'cause I always want a magnesium,

536
00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:57.120
especially if someone's taking a thiazide.

537
00:21:57.120 --> 00:21:59.130
If magnesium is low, it's almost impossible

538
00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:00.960
to get the potassium back up to normal

539
00:22:00.960 --> 00:22:02.823
until you normalize magnesium first.

540
00:22:04.680 --> 00:22:07.680
We used to panic a whole lot about diabetes and thiazides,

541
00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:09.780
oh my gosh, you can't mix the two together.

542
00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:12.600
The blood sugar increase of the thiazide is pretty minimal,

543
00:22:12.600 --> 00:22:13.830
it's not gonna move someone

544
00:22:13.830 --> 00:22:18.270
from a fasting sugar of 80 to a fasting sugar of 400.

545
00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:19.590
Most people are not gonna notice

546
00:22:19.590 --> 00:22:21.600
a 3 to 5 milligram per deciliter change

547
00:22:21.600 --> 00:22:22.620
in their blood sugar.

548
00:22:22.620 --> 00:22:25.913
So diabetes is not a contraindication to thiazides.

549
00:22:25.913 --> 00:22:28.110
You can see a slight bump in triglycerides as well,

550
00:22:28.110 --> 00:22:30.363
again, not typically clinically significant.

551
00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:33.200
Big thing to know is,

552
00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:35.910
all the way back to medical school to physiology,

553
00:22:35.910 --> 00:22:39.840
and recall where the thiazide diuretics work

554
00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:42.900
at the level of the distal convoluted tubule,

555
00:22:42.900 --> 00:22:45.480
meaning as GFR declines,

556
00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:47.910
and now, thankfully, most of our lab computers

557
00:22:47.910 --> 00:22:49.350
are not just reporting creatinine

558
00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:51.420
but also reporting estimated GFR,

559
00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:53.280
super helpful thing.

560
00:22:53.280 --> 00:22:56.640
As GFR declines, and 30 is usually considered the threshold,

561
00:22:56.640 --> 00:22:58.093
the fluid delivery to the distal tubule

562
00:22:58.093 --> 00:23:01.470
where the thiazides work becomes so little

563
00:23:01.470 --> 00:23:04.440
that they become essentially ineffective.

564
00:23:04.440 --> 00:23:07.047
Not that they're supremely effective of the GFR of 31

565
00:23:07.047 --> 00:23:09.120
and they don't work at all at 29,

566
00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:12.630
it's a progressive decline of thiazide efficacy.

567
00:23:12.630 --> 00:23:15.570
But once you cross roughly the 30 threshold,

568
00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:18.210
so when you're moving from CKD 3 to 4,

569
00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:19.220
that's the point where thiazide

570
00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:21.510
is typically not considered useful.

571
00:23:21.510 --> 00:23:23.910
And in that case, switch over to a loop diuretic,

572
00:23:23.910 --> 00:23:25.173
very reasonable there.

573
00:23:26.271 --> 00:23:28.620
And in case you didn't recall metolazone

574
00:23:28.620 --> 00:23:31.770
or brand name Zaroxolyn, is actually a thiazide diuretic.

575
00:23:31.770 --> 00:23:33.030
We don't use it for hypertension.

576
00:23:33.030 --> 00:23:35.880
We almost always, if not always use it

577
00:23:35.880 --> 00:23:37.290
in conjunction with a loop diuretic

578
00:23:37.290 --> 00:23:40.650
to accentuate the efficacy of a loop diuretic.

579
00:23:40.650 --> 00:23:44.160
But metolazone is technically a thiazide-like diuretic,

580
00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:48.033
but it still retains its efficacy with lower GFR.

581
00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:53.850
Here's dosing: If you're an HCTZ fan

582
00:23:53.850 --> 00:23:56.010
and you wanna practice evidence-based medicine,

583
00:23:56.010 --> 00:23:58.260
the trials that used HCTZ

584
00:23:58.260 --> 00:24:01.443
and show cardiovascular outcomes are exactly zero.

585
00:24:03.660 --> 00:24:06.420
Chlorthalidone in the newest hypertension guidelines

586
00:24:06.420 --> 00:24:07.440
is always preferred.

587
00:24:07.440 --> 00:24:09.510
There's probably the most outcomes data

588
00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:12.360
using chlorthalidone, going all the way back to "ALLHAT."

589
00:24:12.360 --> 00:24:14.280
Even the most recent "SPRINT" trial

590
00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:16.950
was a chlorthalidone preferred trial.

591
00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:20.100
Indapamide, if you're curious, I love indapamide

592
00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:22.740
for patients who are milligram phobic.

593
00:24:22.740 --> 00:24:25.350
So like, "Oh you know, so many milligrams.

594
00:24:25.350 --> 00:24:26.400
Yeah, we're gonna start

595
00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:28.298
a little 1 1/4 milligram of indapamide."

596
00:24:28.298 --> 00:24:29.790
(audience laughs)
<v ->Oh my God.</v>

597
00:24:29.790 --> 00:24:31.560
<v ->It sometimes is more palatable.</v>

598
00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:33.840
So keep that little fact in mind.

599
00:24:33.840 --> 00:24:35.190
If people are milligram phobic,

600
00:24:35.190 --> 00:24:38.610
indapamide is your buddy, plus it's a good diuretic.

601
00:24:38.610 --> 00:24:42.570
ACE inhibitors/ARBs, again, CKD or diabetes,

602
00:24:42.570 --> 00:24:45.033
ACE inhibitor or ARB should be on the ticket.

603
00:24:46.110 --> 00:24:51.110
We've long debated, "Are ACE inhibitors better than ARBs?"

604
00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:53.070
For quite a few years,

605
00:24:53.070 --> 00:24:54.840
the answer was typically yes,

606
00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:57.300
mostly because there was just a larger body of evidence

607
00:24:57.300 --> 00:24:59.850
behind ACE inhibitors, they've been around longer.

608
00:24:59.850 --> 00:25:02.940
At this point, they're really considered to be at par

609
00:25:02.940 --> 00:25:05.010
in terms of cardiovascular outcomes.

610
00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:06.720
And if you recognize

611
00:25:06.720 --> 00:25:08.790
that African American patients have typically

612
00:25:08.790 --> 00:25:11.010
a 2 to 4 time greater likelihood

613
00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:14.610
of developing angioedema with ACE inhibitors over ARBs,

614
00:25:14.610 --> 00:25:16.920
all things being equal, if you're on a quandary

615
00:25:16.920 --> 00:25:19.290
and the patient in front of you is African American,

616
00:25:19.290 --> 00:25:21.720
myself, I pick ARBs preferentially

617
00:25:21.720 --> 00:25:23.340
just 'cause why would I pick a drug

618
00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:25.740
that's got equal outcomes data

619
00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:27.480
but is gonna increase the risk of angioedema

620
00:25:27.480 --> 00:25:28.773
more than another option.

621
00:25:30.300 --> 00:25:33.540
So again, we don't use 'em together in the same patient.

622
00:25:33.540 --> 00:25:36.360
The cough is due to bradykinin accumulation.

623
00:25:36.360 --> 00:25:37.920
When people see angioedema,

624
00:25:37.920 --> 00:25:40.800
it is not an allergic-induced problem,

625
00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:42.633
so steroids don't help.

626
00:25:43.710 --> 00:25:44.610
What do you do if someone

627
00:25:44.610 --> 00:25:46.650
has angioedema with an ACE inhibitor?

628
00:25:46.650 --> 00:25:48.480
Can you use an ARB?

629
00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:50.700
The answer is, "Sometimes,"

630
00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:53.160
and our nephrologist and our ICU docs

631
00:25:53.160 --> 00:25:54.630
will typically draw the line

632
00:25:54.630 --> 00:25:56.970
at if this patient had angioedema

633
00:25:56.970 --> 00:25:59.550
to the extent that they ended up in the ICU,

634
00:25:59.550 --> 00:26:01.470
intubated for airway protection

635
00:26:01.470 --> 00:26:05.040
or because there was risk of needing airway protection

636
00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:07.890
on an ACE inhibitor, then skip the ARBs as well.

637
00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:12.150
Short of that, the risk of ARB-induced angioedema

638
00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:13.470
is incredibly tiny compared

639
00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:15.270
to ACE inhibitor-induced angioedema.

640
00:26:18.240 --> 00:26:21.540
Here are some representative drugs.

641
00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:23.490
I put incidentally,

642
00:26:23.490 --> 00:26:25.380
the ones that are in italics here,

643
00:26:25.380 --> 00:26:26.213
and this is just me,

644
00:26:26.213 --> 00:26:28.290
these are drugs that are actually more potent

645
00:26:28.290 --> 00:26:30.540
and better blood pressure reduction drugs,

646
00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:33.600
than the others that are not in italics.

647
00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:34.860
Take that for what it's worth,

648
00:26:34.860 --> 00:26:38.130
but there are some ARBs and some ACE inhibitors.

649
00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:39.090
Calcium-channel blockers.

650
00:26:39.090 --> 00:26:41.280
Like I said, when you read guidelines

651
00:26:41.280 --> 00:26:43.290
and it says a calcium-channel blocker,

652
00:26:43.290 --> 00:26:44.460
the assumption is always

653
00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:47.640
a long-acting dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker,

654
00:26:47.640 --> 00:26:49.540
which is any drug that ends in "pine".

655
00:26:50.550 --> 00:26:52.920
The non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers

656
00:26:52.920 --> 00:26:54.960
we don't commonly use for hypertension,

657
00:26:54.960 --> 00:26:57.150
that's verapamil and diltiazem.

658
00:26:57.150 --> 00:26:59.670
Recall, verapamil and diltiazem,

659
00:26:59.670 --> 00:27:02.880
verapamil to a slightly larger extent than diltiazem,

660
00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:04.740
slow AV conduction.

661
00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:08.168
Very useful drugs when you have tachy arrhythmias

662
00:27:08.168 --> 00:27:10.740
that involve the AV node,

663
00:27:10.740 --> 00:27:13.950
diltiazem and verapamil can be very useful there,

664
00:27:13.950 --> 00:27:15.690
less effective for blood pressure reduction,

665
00:27:15.690 --> 00:27:17.640
they're also negative inotropes.

666
00:27:17.640 --> 00:27:19.350
So in heart failure,

667
00:27:19.350 --> 00:27:20.220
and we'll come to this tomorrow

668
00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:21.840
when we talk about heart failure,

669
00:27:21.840 --> 00:27:24.060
you can still use a dihydropyridine,

670
00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:26.790
the non-dihydropyridine, verapamil or diltiazem,

671
00:27:26.790 --> 00:27:29.390
as negative inotropes are not used in heart failure.

672
00:27:31.200 --> 00:27:34.020
Plus verapamil is super constipating.

673
00:27:34.020 --> 00:27:37.080
So if you have someone with mild hypertension

674
00:27:37.080 --> 00:27:39.060
'cause it's not a very good blood pressure-reducing drug,

675
00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:42.150
and chronic diarrhea, maybe pick verapamil,

676
00:27:42.150 --> 00:27:43.563
otherwise not so much.

677
00:27:45.240 --> 00:27:48.720
Recall when we're talking about heart failure,

678
00:27:48.720 --> 00:27:51.180
there are only three beta blockers that are approved

679
00:27:51.180 --> 00:27:53.490
and have good data for heart failure.

680
00:27:53.490 --> 00:27:55.890
Most guidelines will kinda nudge you

681
00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:59.220
toward these three drugs because of the beta blockers

682
00:27:59.220 --> 00:28:00.780
that are out in existence,

683
00:28:00.780 --> 00:28:02.850
these three have the best data,

684
00:28:02.850 --> 00:28:03.840
not just in heart failure

685
00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:06.210
but in ischemic heart disease as well.

686
00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:07.320
From heart failure standpoint,

687
00:28:07.320 --> 00:28:09.720
remember it's metoprolol succinate, not the tartrate,

688
00:28:09.720 --> 00:28:13.565
the BID version, the succinate is the once a day version,

689
00:28:13.565 --> 00:28:14.970
carvedilol and bisoprolol,

690
00:28:14.970 --> 00:28:16.890
but that does not mean that other beta blockers

691
00:28:16.890 --> 00:28:19.200
are not useful for blood pressure reduction,

692
00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:21.150
these three have the best outcome data.

693
00:28:23.580 --> 00:28:25.560
Once we see ischemic heart disease,

694
00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:27.900
again, the hypertension guidelines

695
00:28:27.900 --> 00:28:29.460
essentially ignore beta blockers,

696
00:28:29.460 --> 00:28:31.710
and have done so for several different iterations

697
00:28:31.710 --> 00:28:33.180
of the guidelines,

698
00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:35.760
mostly because outcomes data with beta blockers

699
00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:39.300
and hypertension are not as good.

700
00:28:39.300 --> 00:28:41.370
Stroke reduction in particular with beta blockers

701
00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:44.400
is not nearly as robust as stroke reduction

702
00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:47.370
with any of the other four classes of drugs,

703
00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:48.870
ACE inhibitors, ARBs, diuretics,

704
00:28:48.870 --> 00:28:51.060
or calcium-channel blockers.

705
00:28:51.060 --> 00:28:52.920
There's still may be reasons

706
00:28:52.920 --> 00:28:55.440
why we would use a beta blocker in hypertension.

707
00:28:55.440 --> 00:28:58.770
And AHA says, "Don't forget about ischemic heart disease.

708
00:28:58.770 --> 00:29:01.260
That's a good indication for a beta blocker."

709
00:29:01.260 --> 00:29:03.510
Recognizing that they do reduce blood pressure,

710
00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:05.850
do improve some cardiovascular outcomes,

711
00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:07.950
especially in ischemic heart disease.

712
00:29:07.950 --> 00:29:10.350
So even though we've got four classes of drugs,

713
00:29:10.350 --> 00:29:13.200
which are initial choices for hypertension,

714
00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:15.180
don't think that there are not other drugs

715
00:29:15.180 --> 00:29:17.490
that we can still use for hypertension.

716
00:29:17.490 --> 00:29:21.060
That's kind of in the general generic sort of patient,

717
00:29:21.060 --> 00:29:23.100
there was the four drugs we'd pick.

718
00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:25.080
Once you start adding in comorbidities,

719
00:29:25.080 --> 00:29:27.750
that'll likely decide for you which drug

720
00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:29.160
is gonna be the best choice.

721
00:29:29.160 --> 00:29:31.380
Alrighty, so we've got a 62-year-old man

722
00:29:31.380 --> 00:29:33.420
who presents for followup of hypertension.

723
00:29:33.420 --> 00:29:35.250
Despite adherence to his daily regimen.

724
00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:38.550
chlorthalidone, carvedilol, amlodipine, lisinopril,

725
00:29:38.550 --> 00:29:40.470
he's got an A, B, C, and D,

726
00:29:40.470 --> 00:29:43.440
all the drugs are there, blood pressure's still high.

727
00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:44.910
Recent labs are normal.

728
00:29:44.910 --> 00:29:46.170
Which of the following adjustments

729
00:29:46.170 --> 00:29:47.280
would be most appropriate

730
00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:49.263
to bring his blood pressure to goal?

731
00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:53.133
The board really likes optimization questions.

732
00:29:54.030 --> 00:29:56.010
We've got all the right things here.

733
00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:57.810
What can we do to further tweak this,

734
00:29:57.810 --> 00:29:59.340
further optimize this regimen?

735
00:29:59.340 --> 00:30:01.390
Basically, what is your drug number five?

736
00:30:02.400 --> 00:30:04.500
So let's see here.

737
00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:06.090
Chlorthalidone to furosemide,

738
00:30:06.090 --> 00:30:08.970
we're told that his chemistry is normal.

739
00:30:08.970 --> 00:30:10.650
Lisinopril to losartan.

740
00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:14.513
Add some isosorbide, or add spironolactone.

741
00:30:18.270 --> 00:30:19.740
Excellent, and I'm hoping this is because

742
00:30:19.740 --> 00:30:20.610
you would've done this

743
00:30:20.610 --> 00:30:23.550
and it's not just the others are bad choices.

744
00:30:23.550 --> 00:30:26.610
Drug number four, and definitely drug number five.

745
00:30:26.610 --> 00:30:28.890
If you have not already used spironolactone,

746
00:30:28.890 --> 00:30:30.270
it should be drug number four,

747
00:30:30.270 --> 00:30:32.400
definitely be drug number five.

748
00:30:32.400 --> 00:30:35.040
That is the sequence to follow.

749
00:30:35.040 --> 00:30:37.260
Resistant hypertension is defined

750
00:30:37.260 --> 00:30:39.120
as persistent blood pressure elevation

751
00:30:39.120 --> 00:30:41.010
despite three or more drugs,

752
00:30:41.010 --> 00:30:43.890
caveats being they have to be in decent doses.

753
00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:47.790
So 2 1/2 of amlodipine doesn't count as a decent dose,

754
00:30:47.790 --> 00:30:51.390
and one must be a diuretic also at an adequate dose.

755
00:30:51.390 --> 00:30:54.280
Heads up, 12 1/2 of HCTZ is not an adequate dose,

756
00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:56.793
25 of chlorthalidone is.

757
00:30:58.140 --> 00:31:00.330
Usually the problem is not us

758
00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:02.070
prescribing inappropriate medications.

759
00:31:02.070 --> 00:31:03.030
Usually the problem is, as you know,

760
00:31:03.030 --> 00:31:04.860
is our patients don't take medications

761
00:31:04.860 --> 00:31:05.970
or they're taking other things

762
00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:08.063
that are screwing with their blood pressure.

763
00:31:09.090 --> 00:31:11.970
Suboptimal, again, usually it's inadequate diuresis.

764
00:31:11.970 --> 00:31:14.640
If the problem is us, use a longer-acting diuretic

765
00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:17.070
or a more potent diuretic, add spironolactone.

766
00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:19.800
The other options were not great options.

767
00:31:19.800 --> 00:31:23.223
Alpha blockers still can be in that as drug five or six.

768
00:31:25.740 --> 00:31:27.750
Aldosterone antagonists, here's the dosing.

769
00:31:27.750 --> 00:31:29.610
Remember that they will increase potassium,

770
00:31:29.610 --> 00:31:31.710
be mindful of that.

771
00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:32.543
Got a 50...

772
00:31:32.543 --> 00:31:35.820
This one appears on the board exam almost always

773
00:31:35.820 --> 00:31:37.140
in one form or another.

774
00:31:37.140 --> 00:31:39.030
57-year-old male with type 2 diabetes,

775
00:31:39.030 --> 00:31:40.770
blood pressure is 148/94,

776
00:31:40.770 --> 00:31:43.710
baseline creatinine is 1.25.

777
00:31:43.710 --> 00:31:45.840
You start lisinopril 20 milligrams.

778
00:31:45.840 --> 00:31:47.610
Blood pressure improves appropriately.

779
00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:49.460
However, creatinine increases to 1.6.

780
00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:52.800
You repeat that a week later it's still unchanged,

781
00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:53.883
what do you do?

782
00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:00.930
Excellent, so most are going

783
00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:03.900
with continue the lisinopril at the same dose.

784
00:32:03.900 --> 00:32:04.980
This is what happened.

785
00:32:04.980 --> 00:32:08.490
You saw a treatment induced decline in renal function.

786
00:32:08.490 --> 00:32:09.690
The number to keep in mind,

787
00:32:09.690 --> 00:32:12.390
the threshold for saying "I'm okay with this"

788
00:32:12.390 --> 00:32:15.240
is 30% increase in creatinine.

789
00:32:15.240 --> 00:32:18.127
Above 30%, you basically take a step back and say,

790
00:32:18.127 --> 00:32:19.320
"Wow, what did I do?

791
00:32:19.320 --> 00:32:21.330
Am I looking at renal artery stenosis?

792
00:32:21.330 --> 00:32:22.950
What exactly happened?"

793
00:32:22.950 --> 00:32:26.190
Up to a 30% increase in creatinine is basically evidence

794
00:32:26.190 --> 00:32:28.860
that you have decreased intraglomerular pressure.

795
00:32:28.860 --> 00:32:29.940
That is a good thing

796
00:32:29.940 --> 00:32:32.070
because elevated intraglomerular pressure

797
00:32:32.070 --> 00:32:34.920
leads to glomerular sclerosis, which ultimately leads

798
00:32:34.920 --> 00:32:36.510
to end-stage renal disease and dialysis,

799
00:32:36.510 --> 00:32:37.713
which we want to avoid.

800
00:32:39.750 --> 00:32:41.940
Difference between hypertensive emergency,

801
00:32:41.940 --> 00:32:44.700
a hypertension with target organ damage.

802
00:32:44.700 --> 00:32:47.250
We don't use the urgency terminology anymore,

803
00:32:47.250 --> 00:32:49.920
it is now considered severe asymptomatic hypertension,

804
00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:51.573
meaning no target organ damage.

805
00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:55.380
Treatment, we don't precipitously lower blood pressure

806
00:32:55.380 --> 00:32:58.230
in cases of asymptomatic hypertension.

807
00:32:58.230 --> 00:33:02.133
The only exception to that rule is aortic dissection.

808
00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:05.190
Non-pharmacologic treatments.

809
00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:07.140
You can read yourself, I have to put this in there

810
00:33:07.140 --> 00:33:09.090
'cause people say, "What about non-drug options?"

811
00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:10.620
There they are.

812
00:33:10.620 --> 00:33:12.630
Less sodium, more potassium,

813
00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:15.360
drink less, exercise more.

814
00:33:15.360 --> 00:33:19.290
This is a quick rundown of systolic and diastolic murmurs

815
00:33:19.290 --> 00:33:21.630
just because it doesn't fit any place else.

816
00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:24.030
The easy way to remember is systolic murmurs

817
00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:26.400
are either going to be narrowing

818
00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:30.540
or stenosis of valves that are open during systole,

819
00:33:30.540 --> 00:33:32.700
i.e. the aortic and pulmonic valves,

820
00:33:32.700 --> 00:33:34.323
or regurgitation of valves

821
00:33:34.323 --> 00:33:36.810
that are typically closed during systole,

822
00:33:36.810 --> 00:33:39.260
which are the AV valve, the mitral and tricuspid.

823
00:33:41.160 --> 00:33:42.660
Remember with aortic stenosis,

824
00:33:42.660 --> 00:33:46.200
common problem, the key thing with aortic stenosis

825
00:33:46.200 --> 00:33:50.550
is that valve area is not the driver for valve replacement,

826
00:33:50.550 --> 00:33:52.620
it is velocities across that valve

827
00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:55.380
or really was what dictates the degree of stenosis.

828
00:33:55.380 --> 00:33:57.450
More often than not, our patients are moving

829
00:33:57.450 --> 00:33:59.880
to non-open valve replacements

830
00:33:59.880 --> 00:34:02.853
with a transcatheter Aortic Valve Replacement or TAVR.

831
00:34:04.020 --> 00:34:06.120
Diastolic murmurs, basically the valves

832
00:34:06.120 --> 00:34:08.087
that should be closed during diastole,

833
00:34:08.087 --> 00:34:09.480
aortic and pulmonic valve,

834
00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:11.040
are either leaking or the valves

835
00:34:11.040 --> 00:34:12.810
that are open during diastole,

836
00:34:12.810 --> 00:34:16.050
which are the mitral and tricuspid valves are stenotic,

837
00:34:16.050 --> 00:34:17.160
those are the ones.

838
00:34:17.160 --> 00:34:18.180
Thank you for your time,

839
00:34:18.180 --> 00:34:21.517
I will wrap up.
(audience applauding)

840
00:34:21.517 --> 00:34:24.100
(upbeat music)

